SparkSession & Dataframe:

SparkSession is the main gateway to intract with spark.

    - Create Dataframe 
    - Run SQL queries 
    - Read data 
    - Write data 
    - Configure Saprk 


Creating Saprk Session :

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
spark=SparkSession.builder\
    .appName("MySparkSessionDemo")\
    .master("local[*]")\
    .config("spark.sql.shuffle.partitions","4")\
    .getOrCreate()


SparkSession        Main entry point 
builder             Used to configure session 
appName             Sets application name 
master              Defines execution mode
config              Sets spark config 
getOrcreate         Creates or reuse session 
Spark.stop()        Stop session 


What is Dataframe 

    - A dataframe is a distributed collection of data orginized into rows and columns with a schema 

        - Data is stored in a tabular formate 
        - It has a column names 
        - Each column has datatype 
        - Data is distributed across multiple machines 



RDD had problems :

Problems                        Explanations 

No Schema                       Spark does not know column structure 

More code 

No Query optimization 


Advatanges of dataframe :

Schema              Columns have define type 

Catalyst Optimizer  Automatic query optimization 

Less Code 

Faster processing 



Creating Dataframes :

    1. From Python List 

    data=[
        (1,"A",30,"Mumbai"),
        (2,"B",31,"Delhi"),
        (3,"C",32,"Pune"),
        (4,"D",33,"Bangalore"),
    ]

    Each row: tuple 
    All rows togather = List 


    spark.createDataFrame(data,columns)

    columns=["id","Name","age","City"]


Check Schema :

    df.printSchema()


2. List of Lists 

    data=[
        [1,"A",30,"Mumbai"],
        [2,"B",31,"Delhi"]
    ]

    column=["id","Name","age","City"]


3. From List of Dictionaries 


4. Creating Dataframe From RDD 

    rdd=spark.sparkContext.parallellize([
        (1,"A",30),
        (2,"B",40)

    ])

    df=spark.createDataFrame(rdd,["id","Name","age"])


5. Explicit Schema 

   from pyspark.sql.types import * 

   StructType:

        - Represents the entire Schema 

    StructField

        - Represents one column 



    schema =StructType([
        StructField(column_name,data type,nullable),
        StructField(column_name,data type,nullable),
        StructField(column_name,data type,nullable),
        StructField(column_name,data type,nullable)
    ])
    nullable: True/False 


    StringType          text 
    FloatType
    